\begin{pmatrix} 2 & 1 \\ -1 & 3\end{pmatrix}$=$\begin{pmatrix} 3 & 5 \\ -5 & 8\end{pmatrix}$. But this is not yet with respect to the basis $e_1+e_2,2e_1-e_2$. The transformation matrix from the basis $e_1+e_2,2e_1-e_2$ to the basis $e_{1},e_{2}$ is $\begin{pmatrix} 1 & 2 \\ 1 & -1\end{pmatrix}$. So the matrix of $A^2$ with respect to the basis $e_1+e_2,2e_1-e_2$ is $\begin{pmatrix} 1 & 2 \\ 1 & -1\end{pmatrix}^{-1}
\begin{pmatrix} 1 & 2 \\ 1 & -1\end{pmatrix}=\begin{pmatrix} 1/3 & 2/3 \\ 1/3 & -1/3\end{pmatrix}
